Using rainfall exclusion systems to simulate crop responses to drought
                    Abderrahim Bouhenache 
            ORCID: orcid.org/0000-0003-2201-13951,2,3

Nature Reviews Earth & Environment

(2026)Cite this article

Subjects

            BiogeochemistryClimate-change impacts

Access through your institution







                        Buy or subscribe

Changes in rainfall regimes caused by climate change threaten global crop production. This risk is particularly acute in Africa where the frequency and intensity of droughts during the growing season are increasing and rainfed agriculture provides food and income for hundreds of millions of people. However, field investigations of drought effects are challenging and largely concentrated in the Northern Hemisphere. Although controlled-environment experiments in which rainfall is manipulated provide general mechanistic understanding of crop responses to drought, these approaches cannot capture real-world interactions with other environmental drivers.These systems can assess crop responses across inter-seasonal gradients of drought intensity. In sub-humid Zimbabwe, this approach has revealed that the effects of changes in rainfall patterns on crop performance far outweigh the effects of management practices across rainfed maize-based systems. Long-term investigations could support the calibration and validation of soil–crop models and improve projections of the impact of climate change on agriculture in Africa.



